:: Gwylan Yearning Door
<<effects>><<run statusCheck("Gwylan")>>

<<if $phase is 0>>
	<<set _seenRoom to true>>
	You turn the knob, and hear someone gasp in surprise on the other side. You enter to see an ornate bedroom.
	Gwylan stands in front of a vanity, rummaging around frantically before turning around.
	<br><br>

	"You really need to learn how to knock!" <<He>> crosses <<his>> arms, closing a drawer behind <<him>>. "It's fine, you've already broken in once. Come in and shut the door behind you." You step inside.
<<elseif $phase is 1>>
	You knock on the door. You hear some rummaging around on the other side, followed by Gwylan's voice. "Come in." You enter.
<<else>>
	There's no keyhole, so you open the door very slowly to take a peek.
	<<skulduggerycheck>>
	<<if $skulduggerysuccess>>
		<<set _seenRoom to true>>
		<span class="green">You open the door in complete silence, just enough to see inside.</span> It's an ornate bedroom. Gwylan stands in front of a vanity, looking down at a small object.
		<br><br>

		It's a pocketwatch on a chain. A very fancy one, too. It looks warped, but otherwise it's shiny and cared for. There's a snowflake etched into the glass.
		<br><br>

		You quietly close the door, and knock. You hear <<him>> rummage around for a moment. "Come in." You enter properly.
	<<else>>
		<span class="red">The door creaks.</span> You hear someone on the other side gasp in surprise, and back away from the door.
		<br><br>

		You hear some rummaging around, followed by Gwylan's voice. "It's okay, you can come in." You step inside.
	<</if>>
<</if>>
<br><br>

<<if !_seenRoom>>
	It's a spacious, ornate bedroom. Gwylan stands in front of a vanity, and shuts a drawer behind <<him>> as you enter.
<<else>>
	The room is spacious.
<</if>>
The bed, covered in frilly red and green blankets, has a canopy and curtains. The view from the solitary window suggests you're quite high up, as you can see some of the treetops.
This must be the shop's tower, although it looks like it could be even higher than that somehow.
